result.text:
“I Wish I Had Hitler’s Generals” — Trump’s Troubling Remark on Loyalty

Alright, so Trump apparently told John Kelly he wished he had “generals like Hitler had.” And that’s…pretty loaded, honestly. 'Cause if you’re saying you want Hitler-style generals, it’s implying you want people around who are super obedient—like the kind of folks who follow orders without a second thought, no matter how extreme or questionable. Hitler’s generals were notorious for doing just that, right? They executed brutal, horrifying orders, often without any moral questioning, all for the sake of loyalty to him and his agenda.

So yeah, saying you want people who are that blindly loyal? It kinda hints at wanting to push boundaries—maybe even legal or ethical ones—without anyone challenging you. And historically, Hitler’s approach with his generals wasn’t just about loyalty; it was about power and control, no questions asked. That’s a mindset that usually has dark goals behind it.

It brings up a lot of concerns because, well, leaders in a democracy ideally don’t aim for that kind of unchecked authority. Generals in the U.S. military, for instance, swear loyalty to the Constitution, not to any one leader. They’re supposed to stand up if they’re told to do something unlawful or wrong. So if someone’s saying, “I wish I had Hitler’s type of generals,” it feels like a wish for something that runs completely against democratic principles—like an army that will do whatever you say, no checks, no balances, no pushback.
